The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 India in arms trade top 100

 Stockholm, June 11 (AFP): World military spending has risen by 37 per cent in 10 years to $1.2 trillion a US-led trend unlikely to be broken soon the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (Sipri) said today.

 US companies and those in western Europe dominated the institutes top 100 list, together accounting for 92 per cent of arms sales in 2005, the latest year for which figures are available.

 Forty US firms accounted for 63 per cent of sales, 32 western European companies had 29 per cent sales and nine Russian companies accounted for 2 per cent. Companies based in Japan, Israel and India accounted for most of the remaining 6 per cent.

 World military expenditure was up 3.5 per cent in 2006 from 2005 and by 37 per cent since 1997, Sipri said in its annual report. The US accounted for 46 per cent of the spending last year and was responsible for 62 per cent of the total increase. It had spent $528.7 billion in 2006. 




